Non-obvious choices here:

**Why newline-JSON, not MCP/JSON-RPC over the wire.**
The whole point of the bridge is that the agent *can't* speak MCP.
Using JSON-RPC framing inside would add ceremony (id fields, error
objects with specific shape) that buys nothing — we're not
multiplexing, we're not long-lived per-connection, and the
debuggability argument (socat / nc testing) is worth keeping. If we
later want proper MCP tools exposed this way we can layer them on; the
wire format is intentionally the least expressive thing that works.

**Verb dispatch doesn't route through McpManager, even though the task
description said it would.**
Reason: the memory/tasks/budget MCP tools that exist today are
accessed through harness containers' own MCP client. They're not
first-class tools exported from the xpressclaw server. So routing
"memory.add" through McpManager::call_tool would require first
creating an "xpressclaw:memory.add" MCP tool and registering it.
Easier to call MemoryManager directly; same outcome. If we later
export these as MCP tools (for MCP-speaking harnesses to consume too),
we can re-route through McpManager without touching the wire format.

**Per-connection model, not persistent.**
Pi's agent loop invokes `xclaw` as a fresh shell subprocess per call —
there's nothing to keep a persistent connection for on the agent side.
Server-side, accepting + dispatching + closing is a few microseconds.
Not worth building connection pooling.

**Positional args collected under _positional.**
Rare but necessary — verbs like `xclaw log info "message with spaces"`
don't naturally fit the flag model. Putting them under a reserved key
keeps the flat-object shape consistent and doesn't force every verb to
predeclare positional positions.

**Why `xclaw` is a second bin in xpressclaw-cli, not its own crate.**
Adding a workspace member costs dependency resolution time and a
build.rs hop. xpressclaw-cli already has the core dep for shared
protocol types; adding one more binary entry is trivial. If xclaw
grows a lot of its own deps later we split it out; today it's 200 LoC
and shares everything with the main CLI.

**Unix-only by design.**
The socket transport is Unix-specific. Windows support would require
named pipes with a different API. The WASM guest doesn't care about
the host OS — it sees a preopened "file" it can read/write. So the
split is contained to this one module. Revisit when/if we have real
Windows user demand.

**Socket path.**
<data_dir>/run/xclaw.sock places it with other xpressclaw state. Not
/tmp (survives reboots if the data_dir is persistent), not /var/run
(requires root), not ~/.xpressclaw (conflicts on shared hosts). The
guest sees it mounted at /run/xclaw.sock per task 4 (the XCLAW_SOCKET
env constant in harness/pi.rs).

**Socket-to-guest bridging NOT implemented in this commit.**
PiHarness in task 4 sets XCLAW_SOCKET=/run/xclaw.sock inside the guest,
but the VolumeMount from host socket to guest /run/xclaw.sock isn't
wired yet. That requires wasmtime-wasi to expose the unix socket as a
preopen, which needs extra care (WASI p1 treats preopens as
directories; a socket needs fd-level passing). Landing that
alongside the actual pi image in a follow-up makes more sense than
doing it speculatively now with no guest to test against.
